{F:00000000000001
{topic:Toolbox Commands}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
The toolbox is shown at the top of the window and contains six icons. Clicking on these gives quick access to useful functions when reading a document. The icons perform the following functions:

{Picture:I,forward}{Index:Forward}{>:12}Forward. This icon moves to the next topic in the order in which the topics are stored in the document. This icon will be grey if you are on the last topic in a document. This command will give access to all topics in the document.
{Picture:I,backward}{Index:Backward}{>:12}Backward. This icon moves to the previous topic in the order in which the topics are stored in the document. This icon will be grey if you are on the first topic in a document. This command will give access to all topics in the document.
{Picture:I,trace}{Index:Back Trace}{>:12}Back Trace. This icon allows you to retrace any movements in the document (except those due to scrolling). This is particularly useful if you have been following cross references and wish to return to the main piece of text at the point where you left it. A large but limited number of movements will be remembered.
{Picture:I,find}{Index:Search}{>:12}Search. This icon opens a dialogue box which allows the text to be searched for index points or for particular words. Click {Ref:here,Searching} for more information about this function.
{Picture:I,mark}{Index:Bookmark}{>:12}Bookmark. This icon opens a dialogue box which allows bookmarks to be placed in the text and to be located.  Click {Ref:here,Bookmarks} for more information about this function.
{Picture:I,index}{Index:Index Icon}{>:12}Index. This icon takes you straight to the index page for the document. While the index page is displayed, the button will be depressed in the toolbox as a reminder.

These functions are all duplicated in the Tools sub-menu of the main program {Ref:menu,Main Menu}.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Main Menu} to find out more about the main menu.
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Searching} to find out more about searching.
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Bookmarks} to find out more about bookmarks.
{F:00000000000001
{topic:Main Menu}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
The main menu is displayed by clicking the {B:MENU} button when the mouse pointer is over the main window. This menu has three options:

{F:2}Save{F:0}{Index:Saving}
The Save option leads to a standard RISC OS save dialogue box which allows the current document to be saved. Do this by typing in the full path name and pressing {B:Return} or by entering a file name and dragging the file icon to a directory viewer. This will save the document along with any bookmarks that may have been placed in the text.

{F:2}Print{F:0}{Index:Printing}
The Print option leads to a dialogue box which shows the name of the currently installed printer driver, if any. If there is no printer driver installed, you will not be able to print. Refer to your RISC OS user guide for more information on printer drivers. Click on the {B:Print} icon to start the printout. If the option for 'This topic only' is selected, you will get a printout of just the displayed topic; otherwise the entire document will be printed. The text is formatted according to the width of paper selected by your printer driver.

{F:2}Tools{F:0}{Index:Tools Menu}
The Tools option leads to a sub-menu containing options which correspond directly with the icons on the toolbox. Refer to the {Ref:Toolbox Commands,Toolbox Commands} topic for more information.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Toolbox Commands} to find out more about the toolbox.
{F:00000000000001
{Topic:What is} {Picture:i,cvlogo}?{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
{Picture:i,cvlogo} is a utility for creating and reading hyper-linked documents. hyper-linking allows the author of a document to mark points in the text which are related to other parts of the document. The reader of the document can follow such references quickly by simply clicking on them with the mouse. This makes it very easy to wander through a document at will, following up interesting trains of thought or ideas, without losing track of the main thread. For most applications, this means that the desired information can be extracted from a document far more quickly, easily and effectively than by more traditional methods.

{Picture:i,cvlogo} is designed specifically to present documents which are mostly text. It is intended to replace a traditional textbook with an electronic equivalent having all the same features and many advantages. The ability to print {Picture:i,cvlogo} documents further extends the flexibility of the system, allowing {Ref:printed,Printing} texts of very high quality to be produced from the material in a {Picture:i,cvlogo} document. Although text is central to the design of {Picture:i,cvlogo}, it is possible to illustrate {Picture:i,cvlogo} documents very easily, even including animations if desired. {Picture:i,cvlogo} undertakes the bulk of the document formatting automatically, leaving authors free to concentrate on the content of their work.

{Picture:i,cvlogo} has many potential applications. Information resources of all sorts may be presented and made more accessible using {Picture:i,cvlogo}. Some typical applications might include:

{>:4}*{>:8}On-line manuals such as this one. {Picture:i,cvlogo} can make creation and distribution of manuals for software quicker, cheaper and more useful to the end-user. Manuals are more easily updated and there is the possibility of interaction with the software.

{>:4}*{>:8}Curriculum resources may be gathered together and presented to pupils in an easily accessible form using {Picture:i,cvlogo}. Pupils are encouraged to explore the information in their own way by following references which interest them.

{>:4}*{>:8}Technical information which is subject to frequent change can be presented in a useful format without compromising the ability to provide regular updates. The Archimedes Virus Reference Document is a good example of this.

{>:4}*{>:8}Complex information being distributed to users with a widely varying level of knowledge is ideally handled by a hyper-linked document. A compact overview can contain references to more detailed explanations of difficult areas, allowing experienced users to gain all the information they need quickly, while those with less knowledge will have no difficulty in finding what they need to know.

{>:4}*{>:8}On-line services can use {Picture:i,cvlogo} documents to provide information containing combinations of text and pictures in one simple file format. Users can download one copy of the {Picture:i,cvlogo} reader allowing them access to easily downloaded {Picture:i,cvlogo} files.

{>:4}*{>:8}Almost any information which might be provided in a book can more usefully be provided in a {Picture:i,cvlogo} file.

In addition to creating, displaying and browsing your own resources there is an ever expanding range of ready-made {Picture:i,cvlogo} files on subjects ranging from European Demographics to fully cross-referenced editions of Shakespeare plays.
{Rule:1}
