{F:00000000000001
{topic:Searching}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
The text may be searched for direct access to any of the cross reference points (including topic names) or for any particular sequence of characters. To start a search, choose the Search option from the {Ref:Tools menu,Tools Menu} or click {B:SEL} over the search icon in the {Ref:toolbox,Toolbox Commands} (The search icon looks like this: {Picture:I,find} ).

{F:2}Finding Cross References{F:0}{Index:Goto/Search}
The Search Text dialogue box will appear when the tool is selected. This is divided into two parts. The top part shows a list of all cross reference points in the text. You may scroll through this list and click {B:SEL} to select any item and then click the {B:Goto} icon to see the part of the text referred to. As a short-cut, double-click {B:SEL} over the entry in the list.

{F:2}Searching For Text{F:0}{Index:Search Text}
The lower part of the dialogue box allows the text to be searched for any word or words. Type some text into the first writeable icon and click the {B:OK} icon to search for it. Note that it does not matter if the text is in upper or lower case (or mixed). The first occurrence of the text will be displayed in the document window, or a message will appear if the text could not be found.

{F:2}Refining the Search{F:0}{Index:Near Icon}{Index:Or Icon}
You may enter text into both the writable icons for a search. In this case, you may select the Or icon or the Near icon between the two pieces of text. If the Or icon is selected, the search will locate any point in the text where either of the entries appears. If the Near icon is selected, the search will only locate points where both entries appear near each other in the text. As an example this could be used to search for SEARCH near TEXT to find out about searching for text without finding all the references to searching and to text.

{F:2}Finding Multiple Occurrences{F:0}{Index:Next Match}
Once the text has been found, you may wish to search for the next place in the document where the same text appears. To do this, select the Next Match icon in the Search Text dialogue before starting the search. The search will then start from the current point instead of from the beginning.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Toolbox Commands} to find out more about the toolbox.
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Cross References} to find out more about cross references.
{F:00000000000001
{topic:Bookmarks}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
Bookmarks may be placed at any point in the text for future reference. These may be referred to by displaying the text associated with any particular bookmark. To create and use bookmarks, choose the Bookmark option from the {Ref:Tools menu,Tools Menu} or click {B:SEL} over the bookmark icon in the {Ref:toolbox,Toolbox Commands} (the bookmark icon looks like this: {Picture:I,mark} ).

{F:2}Using a Bookmark{F:0}{Index:Goto/Bookmark}
The Bookmarks dialogue box will appear when the tool is selected. This is divided into two parts. The top part shows a list of all bookmarks currently set in the text. You may click {B:SEL} to select any of them and then click the {B:Goto} icon to see the part of the text referred to. As a short-cut, double-click {B:SEL} over the entry in the list.

{F:2}Maintaining Bookmarks{F:0}
When any bookmark is selected, you can click the {B:Delete} icon to remove it from the list. This will occur immediately and without warning, so be careful! To create a new bookmark, type the name you wish to give the bookmark into the writable icon in the lower part of the dialogue box. When the name is correct, click the {B:Create} icon and a new bookmark will be created referring to the currently displayed section of text. Note that the mark actually refers to the first word visible in the window and this will be positioned at the top of the window when the bookmark is selected in the future. This may result in a slightly different view of the text if the window is a different width at the time.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Toolbox Commands} to find out more about the toolbox.
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Cross References} to find out more about cross references.
{F:00000000000001
{topic:Iconbar Menu}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
The main menu is displayed by clicking the {B:MENU} button when the mouse pointer is over the iconbar icon. This menu has two options:

{F:2}Info{F:0}{Index:Info}
This option displays a dialogue box which gives information about the software. There are fields showing the name of the program, the purpose of the program, the author, the version number and the ownership. The ownership is particularly important because it tells you who is allowed to use the software according to the {ref:licence,Licences} agreement. The version number should be quoted in all communications relating to this software.

{F:2}Quit{F:0}{Index:Quit}
This option terminates execution of the software. you should use this when you have finished reading documents, to free the memory used for other applications.
{Rule:1}
