{F:00000000000001
{topic:Versions}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
{picture:i,cvlogo} is available in three different {Ref:versions,Types of Software}. These are referred to as types E,S and A for Evaluation, Standard and Advanced.

The Evaluation (E) version is a working copy of the software and may be used to read documents. However, it has no {Ref:printing,Printing} or {ref:saving,Saving} facilities and has some restrictions in other areas. If you run into any of these restrictions, a message will appear to say what has happened.

The Standard (S) version has no restrictions and is able to save documents and to print them. This is the version most people are expected to use, but it has no facilities for creating new documents.

The Advanced (A) version is similar to the standard version but includes a sophisticated compiler allowing hyper-linked documents to be created easily from text, sprite and draw files.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Ownership} to find out more about determining the type of software.
{F:00000000000001
{topic:Licences}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
All Binary Star software is supplied for use governed by the terms of a licence. This licence tells you what you are allowed to do with the software and how you may use it. There are four types of {Ref:licence agreement,Types of Licence} which apply to Binary Star software.

To find out{Index:Ownership} which licence you have, look at the Info box for the software you are using. This is generally done by clicking the {B:MENU} button over the iconbar icon for the software and choosing the Info option. This will display a box giving various information about the program. Among the items displayed is an Owner field. This field contains a two character code followed by some information. The first character of the code indicates the {Ref:type of software,Types of Software}. The second character indicates the {Ref:type of licence,Types of Licence} the use of the software is governed by. The following information qualifies the licence where appropriate, eg a site licence may indicate the name of the site.

If you do not agree with the terms of the licence for the software you are using, you should immediately obtain a version with a more appropriate licence. If you do not wish to do this, you should immediately destroy all copies of the software in your possession and cease using it on any machine.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Types of Licence} to find out more about the different types of licence.
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Types of Software} to find out more about the different types of software.
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Pricing} to find out more about licence costs.
{F:00000000000001
{topic:Types of Licence}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
There are four types of {Ref:licence agreement,Licences} which apply to Binary Star software. These are identified by the second character in the Owner field of the Info box for the software. The possible characters are as follows:

{F:2}{B:P}{>:10}Public Domain.{Index:PD Licence}
{F:0}{>:10}This type of licence allows the software to be copied freely and distributed at will. You may do this as long as ALL the files, including any documentation, are copied and distributed together. You may not separate the files supplied. You may not distribute the software to make a profit, directly or indirectly. A small handling charge may reasonably be levied but this should not exceed a level indicated by the average cost of discs from public domain libraries (about £1.50 including the cost of the disc, at time of writing). If you wish to include the software 'free' with any product you are selling, you need an extended licence to do this.
{F:2}{B:1}{>:10}Single User.{Index:Single User Licence}
{F:0}{>:10}This type of licence allows the software to be used by one person on one machine. The software may be freely copied for backup purposes but these copies may not be distributed.
{F:2}{B:S}{>:10}Site Licence.{Index:Site Licence}
{F:0}{>:10}This type of licence allows the software to be used on up to 30 machines at the same site, by all legitimate users at that site. The software may be freely copied for backup purposes and to install on the machines covered by the agreement but these copies may not be distributed.
{F:2}{B:X}{>:10}Extended.{Index:Extended Licence}
{F:0}{>:10}This type of licence is provided by special negotiation in situations where none of the others is suitable. The terms will vary in each case. You will need to find the written agreement which defines the terms of this type of licence.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Ownership} to find out more about determining the type of licence.
{F:00000000000001
{topic:Types of Software}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
Each Binary Star product may be available in one of three versions. The type of software is indicated by the first character of the owner field of the software. The possible characters are as follows:

{F:2}{B:E}{>:10}Evaluation.{Index:Evaluation Software}
{F:0}{>:10}This is a simple version of the software with many facilities disabled or not present. It is intended to allow the software to be evaluated and tested as well as providing basic functionality as an introduction to the facilities available.
{F:2}{B:S}{>:10}Standard.{Index:Standard Software}
{F:0}{>:10}This is the standard version of the software which most people will use. It will have all the facilities needed for day to day use of the software and will suit the purposes of most users.
{F:2}{B:A}{>:10}Advanced.{Index:Advanced Software}
{F:0}{>:10}This is the most complete version of the software and will contain some special features for more intensive users. It will have extra facilities which some users will find useful.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
 *{>:5}Click {Ref:here,Ownership} to find out more about determining the type of software.
{F:00000000000001
{topic:Pricing}{F:0}{Rule:0}{Picture:R,Logo}
Binary Star software is priced according to the individual product, the type of software and the type of licence agreement it is governed by. There are generally four types of {Ref:licence agreement,Types of Licence} and three {Ref:types of software,Types of Software}. The prices are controlled by various rules.

 *{>:5}Type E (evaluation) software is usually governed by a type P (public domain) licence and is therefore practically free of charge.
 *{>:5}Software governed by a type P (public domain) licence is practically free of charge. The actual price depends on the supplier.
 *{>:5}Software governed by a type S (site) licence is three times the price of the same software when governed by a type 1 (single user) licence.
 *{>:5}Software governed by a type X (extended) licence varies in price. The actual price is negotiated when the licence is defined.
{Rule:1}
{F:3
